Production designer Stuart Craig was tasked with making the staircases "move". He first considered an escalator-like moment, but eventually conceived the square staircase, made up of many stairs that could swing 90 degrees to make different 'bridges'.

At 250 feet by 120 feet, the Chamber of Secrets set was one of the largest built for the films. When we see the Chamber again briefly in the final film the set was entirely reconstructed digitally with green screens as the original had been taken down.

Each Gryffindor boy's bed was personalized by set decorators to highlight each character. Dean Thomas's, a Muggle-born from London, is adorned with decorations featuring his favorite Muggle football team ‚Äî West Ham.
During filming, the crew pretended the Honeydukes sweets were covered with a lacquer to make them last longer. In fact, they were just trying to stop the cast from eating them all!
To create an ethereal movement for the Dementors, filmmakers used reference shots of fabric moving underwater.
Professor McGonagall's Animagus was played by Mrs. P. Head ‚Äî a tabby cat who already had the required 'spectacle' markings and therefore needed no computer effects.

As a subterranean location, production designers were inspired by London Tube stations from the early 1900s when creating the Ministry of Magic. These heavily influenced the extravagant use of ceramic tiles in the Ministry set.

Designer Miraphora Mina had two mottos engraved on the Time-Turner. One on the outer ring reads "I mark the hours every one, nor have I yet outrun the sun", and on the inner ring: "My use and value unto you depends on what you have to do".
The Knight Bus was created by cutting the top off a genuine London Routemaster bus and adding an additional level. Triple-deckers might catch on?

When they arrived at the open casting call for Fred and George, James and Oliver Phelps quickly realized they were the only twins not wearing matching clothes, and so they ran to the nearest shop to buy matching t-shirts.

The filmmakers thought John Williams' musical composition for the scene featuring the first-years traveling across the lake was so good, that they ended up editing this scene to be longer than planned to allow for the entire piece of music to play.
At 37 years old, actor Shirley Henderson was the oldest actor to portray a Hogwarts student when she played a 14-year-old Moaning Myrtle in Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets.

After sending in a form and photograph to audition for Ron Weasley, Rupert Grint didn't hear back from the filmmakers for a while. So, he decided to instead send in a video of himself rapping reasons why he should get the part and landed an audition.
The Black family tapestry was a real prop, woven for the films and hand painted. However, Bellatrix's face was added with VFX in post-production as Helena Bonham Carter had not been cast.

For her date with Harry at Slughorn's Christmas party, actress Evanna Lynch helped make Luna's costume ‚Äî this included making an intricate bracelet out of tinsel, featuring a tinsel hare (Luna's Patronus).
Described in the books as looking like "a Christmas card", the Hogsmeade set was in fact just the Diagon Alley set redressed and covered in fake snow!

There were 500 potions bottles used to dress Snape‚Äôs classroom in the first film. They were filled with dried herbs, baked animal bones, and bits of plastic animal toys taken from the London Zoo gift shop.
House-specific Hogwarts uniforms were never described in the original books, this concept was introduced by Judianna Makovsky ‚Äî costume designer on Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone.
The creatures effects and special effects crews teamed up to create a real mechanical dragon for the caged Horntail scene, complete with a working flamethrower.
The exterior shots of Hogwarts were filmed using a scale model that was over 50ft wide. The model is incredibly detailed, even housing miniature owls in the Owlery and hinges on the doors.

I've had many opportunities in this business but none more important than crossing paths with Clint. #WBFilmmakers
I can't tell you how many times, on a set, when I'm directing a difficult scene, I ask myself, "How would Clint handle this?"
I once asked Clint how he dealt with films he was proud of that didn't connect with audiences commercially. His answer - "make another one."
@Sean_OConnell I called the LA number - rang thirty times, no answer. Called Carmel and he answered on the tenth ring. Old School, baby!
@Sean_OConnell On The Founder I needed to get in touch with him for some reason and I had two land line phone numbers. One in LA and one in Carmel. No answering machine on either.
@Sean_OConnell He's truly one of a kind.
@Sean_OConnell @ReelBlend Gosh, that's hard, Sean. Of course, selfishly I say the 2000s when I was working with him.
It's amazing how actors fall into his pace and enjoy it, even when it's different than their prior experiences. He makes everyone on the set feel like it's their movie.
they'd both just recently won Best director Oscars so it was a master class. #WBFilmmakers
Kevin Costner was also very generous. We met every day and I prepared the days work as though I was directing. Very helpful.
Clint was so generous to me. When we did A Perfect World he really hadn't allowed writers on the set much, I believe. I begged him and he allowed me to sit, watch and learn a lot.
@BatKilmer His immense talent for starters. DW told me that Clint is one of his heroes - admires him greatly.

@JakesTakes @ReelBlend John, please. I learned almost everything I know about directing from Clint. Most importantly how a set should be run. Hire talented people, be kind to everyone and let them do their jobs well.
@Sean_OConnell I hope so!
Hard question, Jake. For me it's director because he was my film school.

In the movies I wrote for Clint, I only saw him angry once. He'd asked for a special lens for a specific shot and someone dropped the ball. He stared at the offender for at least ten seconds then said, "I asked for it."
Clint called me once while he was making Bridges, to check on my progress on an adaptation I was doing for him. I asked him when he'd be back in town and he said, "Ive been back two weeks."
Don Siegel remains, perhaps, the most underrated American director.
Fatal Attraction owes everything to Misty
I could watch Unforgiven once a month. He had just finished shooting it when I met with him on A Perfect World. He compared my script to Lonely Are The Brave, which was high praise.
My last tweet was actually also my first one, so bear with me. Clint was, and continues to be, my mentor (even if he doesn't know it).
